## Part 1: Root Cause Analysis — Why Is It Slow?

### The Full Request Path (What Actually Happens)

When the user clicks "Process", here is the **exact chain** of events with file references:

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Browser
    participant NextJS as Next.js API Route
    participant Python as Python FastAPI
    participant Disk as File System

    Browser->>NextJS: XHR POST /api/ocr/process (multipart)
    NextJS->>Disk: Write each file to tmp/ (writeTempFile)
    NextJS->>Python: axios POST /api/ocr/process (re-upload via FormData stream)
    Python->>Disk: Write each file again (aiofiles to uploads/)
    Python->>Python: detect_pdf_type() → digital or scanned
    alt Scanned PDF
        Python->>Python: pdf2image convert_from_path(dpi=120)
        Python->>Python: deskew_image() per page
        Python->>Python: PaddleOCR extract_ocr_rows() per page
    end
    Python-->>NextJS: JSON response
    NextJS->>Disk: persistOcrDocument() — save file again + DB writes
    NextJS-->>Browser: JSON response
```

### Bottleneck #1: Triple File Write (The "Upload" Illusion)

The user perceives "upload" as slow, but the browser finishes transmitting bytes quickly. What the user is **actually waiting on** is this chain:

| Step | File | What Happens | Time Cost |
|------|------|-------------|-----------|
| 1 | [route.ts L62-70](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/bank-ocr-system/src/app/api/ocr/process/route.ts#L62-L70) | Next.js reads each `File` from formData, converts to `Buffer`, writes to `tmp/` | ~0.5-2s per file |
| 2 | [route.ts L72-79](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/bank-ocr-system/src/app/api/ocr/process/route.ts#L72-L79) | Next.js creates a **new** FormData with `fs.createReadStream` and POSTs via axios to Python | Full re-upload over HTTP (~1-3s per file) |
| 3 | [ocr.py L63-67](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/routers/ocr.py#L63-L67) | Python `write_file()` saves the uploaded file **again** to `uploads/` via aiofiles | ~0.5-1s per file |
| 4 | [ocr.py L471-476](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/routers/ocr.py#L471-L476) | `process_single_statement()` runs synchronously — **blocks the entire async event loop** | 5-120s per file |
| 5 | [route.ts L99-113](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/bank-ocr-system/src/app/api/ocr/process/route.ts#L99-L113) | Next.js saves the file a **third time** via `persistOcrDocument()` to `uploads/{userId}/{statementId}/` | ~0.5-1s per file |

> [!CAUTION]
> **The file is written to disk 3 separate times before processing even begins returning to the user.** For a 5MB PDF, that's ~15MB of redundant I/O.

### Bottleneck #2: Synchronous OCR on the Async Event Loop

In [ocr.py L475](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/routers/ocr.py#L475):
```python
result = process_single_statement(target_path)  # SYNC call inside async endpoint
```

`process_single_statement()` is a **blocking function** called inside an `async def` endpoint. This means:
- The entire uvicorn event loop freezes during OCR processing
- No other requests can be served
- The frontend XHR connection stays open, showing "uploading" the whole time

### Bottleneck #3: Scanned PDF → Image Conversion

In [preprocessor.py L77-89](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/services/preprocessor.py#L77-L89):
```python
def preprocess_scanned_pdf(file_path: Path, dpi: int = 300) -> List[np.ndarray]:
    images = convert_from_path(str(file_path), dpi=dpi)
```

Despite the function signature saying `dpi=300`, the actual **caller** in [ocr.py L163](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/routers/ocr.py#L163) passes `dpi=120`:
```python
images = preprocess_scanned_pdf(file_path, dpi=120)
```

> [!NOTE]
> DPI 120 is **too low** for reliable OCR of small text (account numbers, fine-print narrations). But raising it increases rendering time significantly. This is a correctness-vs-speed tradeoff that currently loses on both fronts — 120 DPI is slow enough to notice but not high enough for accuracy.

### Bottleneck #4: Sequential Per-File Processing

In [ocr.py L471-476](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/routers/ocr.py#L471-L476):
```python
for upload in files:
    # ...
    result = process_single_statement(target_path)
```

Files are processed **one at a time, sequentially**. Upload 5 PDFs → each waits for the previous one to finish before starting.

### Bottleneck #5: PaddleOCR Cold Start

In [ocr_engine.py L25-40](file:///c:/Users/udgee/bank_ocr_system/backend-python/app/services/ocr_engine.py#L25-L40):
```python
def _get_paddle_ocr():
    global paddle_ocr
    if paddle_ocr is None:
        from paddleocr import PaddleOCR
        paddle_ocr = PaddleOCR(lang="en", ...)
```

The first scanned PDF triggers PaddleOCR model loading (~3-8 seconds). This is a one-time cost per server restart, but the user experiences it as part of the first upload being "stuck."

### Speed Summary

| Phase | Time for 1 Scanned 10-page PDF | Bottleneck Severity |
|-------|-------------------------------|-------------------|
| Triple file I/O | 2-4s | 🟡 Medium |
| pdf2image rendering (120 DPI) | 5-15s | 🔴 High |
| PaddleOCR per page (CPU, sequential) | 30-90s (3-9s × 10 pages) | 🔴 Critical |
